(26, 3, 'Researchers needed a framework that could account for cultural differences in responses to adversity'),
(26, 4, 'The original theory could not explain why individuals respond differently to the same uncontrollable situations'),
(27, 1, 'directing their frustration outward and blaming external circumstances for their difficulties'),
(27, 2, 'developing severe and persistent helplessness that generalizes across multiple areas of life'),
(27, 3, 'actively seeking social support networks to compensate for their perceived inadequacies'),
(27, 4, 'experiencing cognitive dissonance that motivates them to reinterpret their failures positively');

